00:22:25.578 --> 00:22:27.205
Hey. buddy. No. no. no!

240
00:22:28.414 --> 00:22:30.382
God.. you're choking me.
I need some air!

241
00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:43.751
- How was your day?
- Good. Buckley. go wash your hands.

242
00:22:43.863 --> 00:22:44.921
Go ahead. buddy.
We'll play after dinner.

243
00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:46.056
Is Susie with you?

244
00:22:46.065 --> 00:22:47.555
- No.
- She's late.

245
00:22:49.068 --> 00:22:51.730
- Lindsey Lou. where's your sister?
- What?

246
00:22:51.737 --> 00:22:54.262
- Your sister.
- She had film club.

247
00:22:55.908 --> 00:22:56.897
What's for dinner. hon?

248
00:23:30.209 --> 00:23:31.767
Shoot!

249
00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:35.947
I hope that was your homework.

250
00:23:38.817 --> 00:23:41.081
Hey.. you're the Salmon girl. right?

251
00:23:41.921 --> 00:23:45.049
- Yeah.
- Remember me? You remember me.

252
00:23:45.124 --> 00:23:48.457
I live right down the street.
down in the green house.

253
00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:49.791
Mr. Harvey.

254
00:23:50.396 --> 00:23:52.455
- Hi.
- Hi. How are you?

255
00:23:52.464 --> 00:23:55.797
- How are your folks doing?
- They're fine.

256
00:23:56.268 --> 00:23:58.634
Good. Tell them I said hi.

257
00:23:58.637 --> 00:24:01.003
You know. you're the perfect person
for me to run into.

258
00:24:01.006 --> 00:24:03.804
because I just built this thing over here
and I want to get a second opinion.

259
00:24:03.809 --> 00:24:05.800
Do you mind taking a look?

260
00:24:06.412 --> 00:24:09.973
Well. actually. Mr. Harvey.
I have to get home.

261
00:24:11.083 --> 00:24:12.675
Okay.

262
00:24:18.657 --> 00:24:20.318
I just worked so hard on it

263
00:24:20.426 --> 00:24:23.020
and I guess I got excited
for someone to see it.

264
00:24:23.028 --> 00:24:24.655
But that's okay.

265
00:24:24.763 --> 00:24:25.991
I'll show the other kids
in the neighborhood.

266
00:24:26.098 --> 00:24:28.328
They're gonna be very excited about it.

267
00:24:30.669 --> 00:24:31.863
Really?

268
00:24:32.671 --> 00:24:35.765
Yeah. It's great.
I mean. it's really neat.

269
00:24:41.513 --> 00:24:43.845
Come on. It'll take two minutes.

270
00:24:48.220 --> 00:24:50.450
You're probably late already.

271
00:24:59.999 --> 00:25:01.557
I don't see anything.

272
00:25:02.201 --> 00:25:03.532
You don't?

273
00:25:04.570 --> 00:25:07.539
You're gonna have to be
more observant. Susie.

274
00:25:32.698 --> 00:25:34.029
What is it?

275
00:25:34.366 --> 00:25:36.766
- I washed my hands!
- Give me five.

276
00:25:36.769 --> 00:25:39.602
Hey. hey. hey. you gotta dry them.
All right.

277
00:25:41.507 --> 00:25:43.771
- Thanks. Mom.
- I'm missing a fork.

278
00:25:44.176 --> 00:25:46.438
- Not beans!
- What?

279
00:25:46.445 --> 00:25:48.504
- Only one.
- One bean?

280
00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:56.581
Pretty neat?

281
00:25:58.424 --> 00:25:59.948
You want a...
You want a pork chop. honey?

282
00:25:59.958 --> 00:26:02.927
- Yes. Thank you.
- Hot. hot!

283
00:26:03.028 --> 00:26:06.259
See? Look at your sister.
great eating habits.

284
00:26:06.265 --> 00:26:08.130
Yeah. but she's older!

285
00:26:09.401 --> 00:26:11.198
- There you go.
- Got it?

286
00:26:11.270 --> 00:26:12.294
Okay.

287
00:26:12.905 --> 00:26:14.463
I built it for the kids in the neighborhood.

288
00:26:14.573 --> 00:26:17.906
I thought they could use it
as kind of a clubhouse. or...

289
00:26:18.710 --> 00:26:20.143
I don't know.

290
00:26:21.080 --> 00:26:23.947
You want to be the first one to try it out?

291
00:26:25.784 --> 00:26:28.446
- Really?
- Yeah. sure. yeah! Go ahead.

292
00:26:28.554 --> 00:26:30.715
It'll be fun. Go ahead.

293
00:26:31.056 --> 00:26:33.456
The corn got into my beans.

294
00:26:33.459 --> 00:26:35.893
If you eat them both.
you can stay up and watch TV with me.

295
00:26:35.961 --> 00:26:37.292
Nah.

296
00:26:37.963 --> 00:26:39.624
I'll make her a plate.

297
00:26:40.799 --> 00:26:42.960
That's it. That's it.

298
00:27:01.219 --> 00:27:02.648
This is neato.

299
00:27:08.627 --> 00:27:10.993
She doesn't like beans.
so I'm not gonna give her any.

300
00:27:10.996 --> 00:27:13.863
Put more. Put more on her plate.
I'm gonna make her eat them all.

301
00:27:13.966 --> 00:27:15.524
Why doesn't she get to eat beans?

302
00:27:15.534 --> 00:27:17.024
Okay. okay. I'm gonna give her beans.

303
00:27:17.035 --> 00:27:19.003
- They're really good.
- Watch this.

304
00:27:19.004 --> 00:27:20.835
- That's better.
- Pile them on.

305
00:27:20.939 --> 00:27:23.499
You think Popeye only eats spinach?
There's beans in that can. too.

306
00:27:30.182 --> 00:27:32.047
Make yourself at home.

307
00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:38.016
- This is really cool. Mr. Harvey.
- Yeah. this is cool?

308
00:27:38.123 --> 00:27:40.387
Yeah. I thought that you kids
would like a place of your own

309
00:27:40.392 --> 00:27:42.326
to. you know. hang out.

310
00:27:45.130 --> 00:27:47.030
Here. Have a seat. Go ahead.

311
00:27:47.633 --> 00:27:51.399
There you go. Sit. You like it?

312
00:27:51.403 --> 00:27:52.870
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

313
00:27:59.311 --> 00:28:01.336
You think she's still at the mall?

314
00:28:02.014 --> 00:28:03.413
- Yeah.
- Really?

315
00:28:03.415 --> 00:28:06.248
- She'll be with Clarissa.
- She could have at least called.

316
00:28:06.251 --> 00:28:07.878
I mean. a 14-year-old girl knows
how to use a telephone.

317
00:28:07.986 --> 00:28:09.044
Can I please...

318
00:28:09.054 --> 00:28:12.581
I understand. I understand.
I'll deal with her when she gets home.

319
00:28:12.691 --> 00:28:15.091
See. I got all these little things.
like this little...

320
00:28:15.093 --> 00:28:19.393
Little. you know. fluffy animals
and some games.

321
00:28:19.398 --> 00:28:20.922
'cause I know you kids
like to play games.

322
00:28:21.033 --> 00:28:22.500
And then. you know. candles

323
00:28:22.568 --> 00:28:25.264
and. you know. little figurines
like these angels.

324
00:28:25.270 --> 00:28:26.760
I thought were so pretty.

325
00:28:26.872 --> 00:28:29.033
All the figurines have little...

326
00:28:32.911 --> 00:28:36.608
Very sweet. And. you know.
some of these little things.

327
00:28:38.083 --> 00:28:39.573
There you go!

328
00:28:40.419 --> 00:28:43.582
It's nice. with the candles
and everything. right?

329
00:28:46.024 --> 00:28:47.855
And there's one rule.

330
00:28:48.594 --> 00:28:50.755
No adults allowed!

331
00:28:58.070 --> 00:28:59.196
Okay?

332
00:29:06.144 --> 00:29:09.113
That's a cute hat.
I like that hat very much.

333
00:29:15.220 --> 00:29:17.745
Would you like a refreshment. Susie?

334
00:29:22.894 --> 00:29:25.727
- Actually. I have to go.
- No. Be polite.

335
00:29:26.598 --> 00:29:28.463
You have to be polite.

336
00:29:29.134 --> 00:29:32.126
Be polite. That's another rule.

337
00:29:49.087 --> 00:29:50.748
It's warm in here.

338
00:29:51.990 --> 00:29:54.486
I'm warm. Are you warm?

339
00:29:55.927 --> 00:29:58.623
You can take your coat off if you want.

340
00:30:13.345 --> 00:30:15.506
You look very pretty. Susie.

341
00:30:16.515 --> 00:30:17.709
Thanks.

342
00:30:22.054 --> 00:30:24.022
Do you have a boyfriend?

343
00:30:30.629 --> 00:30:35.157
No? I knew it. See. I knew you weren't
like those other girls. I knew that.

344
00:30:36.335 --> 00:30:38.030
Mr. Harvey?

345
00:30:38.637 --> 00:30:42.733
It's nice down here. isn't it? It's special.
It's special down here. right?

346
00:30:42.841 --> 00:30:46.709
Yes. It is. It's very special.

347
00:30:58.824 --> 00:31:00.314
I have to go.

348
00:31:01.727 --> 00:31:03.752
I don't want you to leave.

349
00:31:07.499 --> 00:31:09.899
I'm not going to hurt you. Susie.

350
00:32:05.123 --> 00:32:08.286
If you see her.
would you please just call? Thank you.

351
00:32:09.227 --> 00:32:11.127
She's not with the Steads.

352
00:32:11.663 --> 00:32:13.324
Where are my keys?

353
00:32:14.966 --> 00:32:16.661
- Where are they?
- I don't know. honey.

354
00:32:16.668 --> 00:32:18.966
In the bowl by the door?
Where are you going?

355
00:32:19.070 --> 00:32:21.504
Jack. could you just wait?

356
00:32:21.606 --> 00:32:24.074
Jack. would you please wait
for the police?

357
00:32:24.142 --> 00:32:26.110
Look. stay by the phone.

358
00:32:33.485 --> 00:32:36.318
Man. she is going to be
in so much trouble.

359
00:32:40.025 --> 00:32:42.653
- Go back to bed. sweetie.
- Okay.

360
00:32:46.665 --> 00:32:48.656
Guys.. this is my little girl. Susie.

361
00:32:48.767 --> 00:32:50.667
She hasn't come home from school.
Have you seen her?

362
00:32:50.769 --> 00:32:51.997
- No. I ain't seen nobody.
- No?

363
00:32:52.003 --> 00:32:53.664
- Sorry.
- Ma'am. could you take a look at this?

364
00:32:53.772 --> 00:32:55.637
Have you seen this little girl?

365
00:32:56.308 --> 00:32:57.775
Sorry. buddy.

366
00:32:58.877 --> 00:33:01.778
Can you take a look at this. please?
It's my little girl. She hasn't come home.

367
00:33:01.847 --> 00:33:03.940
- Sorry.
- Just take a look at that.

368
00:33:05.116 --> 00:33:07.516
Ma'am. have you seen this girl?
Please. can you just take a look?

369
00:33:20.699 --> 00:33:24.897
Susan has been missing for.
what is it. 4 hours now?

370
00:33:24.903 --> 00:33:27.371
Susie. We call her Susie.

371
00:33:27.873 --> 00:33:30.637
Yeah. a little more than 4 hours.

372
00:33:31.209 --> 00:33:33.370
This the first time she's run away?

373
00:33:33.378 --> 00:33:35.039
She didn't run away. She's...

374
00:33:35.814 --> 00:33:38.009
- She's missing.
- Any problems at home?

375
00:33:40.585 --> 00:33:42.382
Family difficulties?

376
00:33:43.488 --> 00:33:47.356
No. there really are no problems.
This is a happy...

377
00:33:47.893 --> 00:33:50.088
She's a happy child.

378
00:33:51.396 --> 00:33:53.762
- She's never done this. Detective. She...
- I understand that.

379
00:33:53.765 --> 00:33:55.062
- I just have to get a sense of...
- She's not home.

380
00:33:55.166 --> 00:33:56.599
- and she always comes home.
- what's going on here.

381
00:33:56.601 --> 00:33:57.590
There's nothing going on.

382
00:33:57.702 --> 00:33:58.691
- She's missing.
- Understood.

383
00:34:00.338 --> 00:34:01.396
If you see her.
please call me. okay?

384
00:34:01.506 --> 00:34:02.598
Sure thing. Jack.

385
00:34:02.607 --> 00:34:04.074
I'll come back
and see you guys in a little while.

386
00:34:04.175 --> 00:34:05.733
All right. Take care.

387
00:34:05.744 --> 00:34:06.836
Dad?

388
00:34:10.282 --> 00:34:13.115
Excuse me. I'm sorry to interrupt you.
My name's Jack Salmon.

389
00:34:13.218 --> 00:34:14.845
- I live right around the corner.
- Dad!

390
00:34:14.920 --> 00:34:20.756
Dad!

391
00:34:33.939 --> 00:34:35.031
Dad!

392
00:34:37.576 --> 00:34:41.137
Can you put together a list
of all her friends and their names.

393
00:34:41.246 --> 00:34:42.474
- contact information...
- Sure.

394
00:34:42.581 --> 00:34:45.209
...and a description
of what she was wearing?

395
00:34:45.283 --> 00:34:47.308
Yes. of course. Well. actually.
I could tell you that right now

396
00:34:47.419 --> 00:34:50.047
if you want to write it down.
She was wearing

397
00:34:50.455 --> 00:34:52.047
a hand-knitted wool hat.

398
00:34:59.464 --> 00:35:01.261
Mom! Dad!

399
00:35:06.137 --> 00:35:07.798
<i>And it has</i>

400
00:35:08.640 --> 00:35:10.631
<i>long. thin tassels.</i>

401
00:35:14.312 --> 00:35:16.803
<i>And she also has...</i>

402
00:35:18.416 --> 00:35:20.577
<i>Well. in fact.
today she didn't wear her scarf.</i>

403
00:35:21.252 --> 00:35:23.345
But she did wear pink gloves.

404
00:35:23.455 --> 00:35:27.619
and she has a beige canvas
schoolbag. and it's got...

405
00:35:28.660 --> 00:35:29.820
Mom?

406
00:35:29.928 --> 00:35:32.829
<i>...rock star buttons pinned to it.</i>

407
00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:38.833
<i>She has Othello inside her bag...</i>

408
00:37:47.966 --> 00:37:50.127
No!

409
00:37:53.571 --> 00:37:59.567
No!

410
00:38:07.652 --> 00:38:09.643
Secure that cordon.

411
00:38:09.754 --> 00:38:12.086
Jesus Christ.
And tape off the rest of the area

412
00:38:12.157 --> 00:38:13.647
before the whole neighborhood
shows up.

413
00:38:14.826 --> 00:38:17.021
Set up the ICP at the school.

414
00:38:20.999 --> 00:38:22.489
What is that?

415
00:38:29.674 --> 00:38:33.337
We found some evidence
in the cornfield behind the school.

416
00:38:33.845 --> 00:38:37.042
There was a cavity in the earth
with a lot of debris.

417
00:38:37.148 --> 00:38:39.673
mostly loose woods and broken crates.

418
00:38:39.684 --> 00:38:42.710
We think it's the remains
of some kind of structure.

419
00:38:42.720 --> 00:38:44.119
And Susie?

420
00:38:47.192 --> 00:38:49.524
We didn't find her. Mrs. Salmon.

421
00:38:50.662 --> 00:38:52.527
That's good. isn't it?

422
00:38:52.997 --> 00:38:55.022
I mean. you found Susie's hat.
but you didn't find her.

423
00:38:55.033 --> 00:38:58.059
which means we really don't even know
if she was there at all. Right?

424
00:38:58.169 --> 00:39:01.627
I mean. that... That... I mean. it's...
It's preferable. right?

425
00:39:12.684 --> 00:39:14.413
We also found blood.

426
00:39:18.523 --> 00:39:20.718
A significant amount of blood.

427
00:39:26.898 --> 00:39:28.388
I'm very sorry.

428
00:39:30.235 --> 00:39:32.726
Hey. we'll get through this.

429
00:39:32.737 --> 00:39:35.001
- How?
- I'm going to take care of you.

430
00:39:35.073 --> 00:39:36.768
- How?
- I'm going to take care of all of us.

431
00:39:36.774 --> 00:39:39.072
- You can't.
- I'll make it right.

432
00:39:39.577 --> 00:39:42.341
You can't make this right. Jack.
You can't.

433
00:39:42.413 --> 00:39:45.280
We're going to find her. I promise.
We'll bring her home.

434
00:40:28.059 --> 00:40:29.959
If you see anything
that's out of the ordinary

435
00:40:30.061 --> 00:40:32.962
or anybody that's out of the ordinary.
please don't hesitate to call us.

436
00:40:32.964 --> 00:40:34.898
- Certainly.
- You have my number.

437
00:40:34.966 --> 00:40:37.958
Or you just come by the police station.
Okay? I'll be there.

438
00:40:37.969 --> 00:40:39.834
- Thank you for your time.
- You're welcome.

439
00:40:39.938 --> 00:40:41.997
- Have a good day.
- You. too.

440
00:40:48.980 --> 00:40:50.641
What's that. a Wagoneer?

441
00:41:29.687 --> 00:41:31.348
- Mr. Harvey.
- Yes?

442
00:41:31.456 --> 00:41:33.515
Detective Len Fenerman.

443
00:41:33.524 --> 00:41:34.889
How do you do?

444
00:41:34.892 --> 00:41:36.883
Do you have some time
for a few questions?

445
00:41:36.894 --> 00:41:39.055
- Certainly. Come in.
- Thanks.

446
00:41:40.231 --> 00:41:41.892
I know why you're here. of course.

447
00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.195
I think
when something like this happens.

448
00:41:44.669 --> 00:41:46.364
you always blame yourself.

449
00:41:47.205 --> 00:41:49.400
All I can think about now is

450
00:41:49.407 --> 00:41:53.241
why didn't I see something or why didn't
I hear something? Because...

451
00:41:54.245 --> 00:41:55.371
Because surely

452
00:41:56.214 --> 00:41:58.705
that young girl must have screamed.

453
00:42:01.586 --> 00:42:03.918
- Did you want...
- No. no. thanks. I'm fine.

454
00:42:04.022 --> 00:42:05.216
But if you could just think back.

455
00:42:05.223 --> 00:42:08.556
I mean. she was wearing a blue jacket.
yellow corduroys.

456
00:42:08.559 --> 00:42:10.550
Similar clothes to these.

457
00:42:11.495 --> 00:42:13.256
This blue jacket here?

458
00:42:13.364 --> 00:42:14.893
The darker blue jacket.

459
00:42:15.199 --> 00:42:17.224
And on the second photograph.
you could see the pants. as well.

460
00:42:17.335 --> 00:42:18.893
I see. Yeah.

461
00:42:19.604 --> 00:42:22.072
No. it does not ring a bell.

462
00:42:22.173 --> 00:42:24.573
But you were at home that day.

463
00:42:24.575 --> 00:42:26.600
- What day?
- Last Wednesday.

464
00:42:26.711 --> 00:42:28.338
Last Wednesday...

465
00:42:46.898 --> 00:42:48.365
Last Wednesday...

466
00:42:48.533 --> 00:42:49.761
No. I was home all day.

467
00:42:50.468 --> 00:42:51.935
I mean. I probably went out

468
00:42:52.036 --> 00:42:54.937
and ran a few errands
or something like that. but. I mean...

469
00:42:56.808 --> 00:42:59.436
I should have been here all day.
for the most part.

470
00:43:00.211 --> 00:43:02.304
- Okay. Good.
- All righty.

471
00:43:02.413 --> 00:43:03.778
- Thanks.
- Yeah.

472
00:43:04.982 --> 00:43:07.883
- You married?
- I was. yeah.

473
00:43:07.952 --> 00:43:09.715
But you have kids.

474
00:43:09.787 --> 00:43:12.620
No. I wish. I wish. But no.

475
00:43:13.558 --> 00:43:15.822
- You mind if I take a look?
- No.

476
00:43:18.996 --> 00:43:21.624
- I make everything myself.
- Really?

477
00:43:21.732 --> 00:43:24.792
Yeah. All this.
I turn all the banisters myself

478
00:43:24.902 --> 00:43:26.836
and make
all the shingles and the furniture.

479
00:43:26.938 --> 00:43:28.462
And I used to do cabinet making.

480
00:43:28.573 --> 00:43:30.632
but there's not much call for that
these days.

481
00:43:30.741 --> 00:43:32.402
Maybe I spend too much time
on these things.

482
00:43:32.477 --> 00:43:35.469
but it's the perfectionist in me. I guess.

483
00:43:35.480 --> 00:43:37.471
- Well. it shows.
- Thank you.

484
00:43:37.482 --> 00:43:40.178
- That's amazing craftsmanship.
- Well...

485
00:43:40.751 --> 00:43:43.584
I took a risk and tried something new
and discovered a talent

486
00:43:43.654 --> 00:43:45.645
that I didn't know I had.

487
00:43:56.501 --> 00:43:58.435
What's that underneath the stairs?

488
00:43:58.903 --> 00:44:00.596
That would be the basement.

489
00:44:10.014 --> 00:44:11.106
Dad?

490
00:44:13.951 --> 00:44:15.816
She's dead. isn't she?

491
00:44:32.370 --> 00:44:34.167
<i>I was slipping away.</i>

492
00:44:35.873 --> 00:44:37.864
<i>That's what it felt like.</i>

493
00:44:39.911 --> 00:44:41.708
<i>Life was leaving me.</i>

494
00:44:47.385 --> 00:44:49.182
<i>But I wasn't afraid.</i>

495
00:44:53.524 --> 00:44:55.185
<i>Then I remembered.</i>

496
00:44:56.894 --> 00:44:59.556
<i>there was something I was meant to do.</i>

497
00:45:01.332 --> 00:45:03.425
<i>somewhere I was meant to be.</i>

498
00:45:21.185 --> 00:45:22.243
Ray?

499
00:45:38.269 --> 00:45:39.361
Ray!

500
00:45:45.142 --> 00:45:46.234
Ray!

501
00:46:59.383 --> 00:47:01.851
Ray! Wait!

502
00:47:10.695 --> 00:47:12.686
Ray!

503
00:49:08.612 --> 00:49:11.638
<i>"If I had but an hour of love</i>

504
00:49:11.649 --> 00:49:14.140
<i>"If that be all is given me</i>

505
00:49:15.653 --> 00:49:18.645
<i>"An hour of love upon this earth"</i>

506
00:49:20.591 --> 00:49:22.855
<i>"I would give my love to thee</i>

507
00:49:24.361 --> 00:49:25.760
<i>"The Moor."</i>

508
00:49:57.127 --> 00:49:59.459
Are you the Moor?

509
00:49:59.964 --> 00:50:01.022
Why?

510
00:50:09.707 --> 00:50:11.868
I think this belongs to you.

511
00:50:19.884 --> 00:50:21.749
Where did you get this?

512
00:50:22.686 --> 00:50:24.017
I found it.

513
00:50:31.161 --> 00:50:34.062
I write poetry. You're quite good.

514
00:50:37.067 --> 00:50:39.399
Don't you have somewhere to go?

515
00:50:40.838 --> 00:50:42.772
You miss her. don't you?

516
00:50:46.010 --> 00:50:48.205
I never knew what dead meant.

517
00:50:49.246 --> 00:50:51.180
I used to think it meant lost.

518
00:50:52.182 --> 00:50:53.376
Frozen.

519
00:50:53.751 --> 00:50:55.241
It means gone.

520
00:50:56.754 --> 00:50:58.085
She's gone.

521
00:51:01.425 --> 00:51:03.086
What if she isn't?

522
00:51:07.097 --> 00:51:09.088
What if she's still here?

523
00:51:18.976 --> 00:51:22.275
- You're not supposed to do that.
- What?

524
00:51:23.547 --> 00:51:26.778
- Who are you?
- She saw you. that girl.

525
00:51:26.784 --> 00:51:30.720
- I think my hand touched hers.
- Yes. that's all it takes.

526
00:51:30.788 --> 00:51:33.450
She carry you now for the rest of her life.

527
00:51:33.557 --> 00:51:36.754
You're not supposed to look back.
You're supposed to keep going.

528
00:51:38.128 --> 00:51:40.756
Hey! Come back! Wait!

529
00:51:41.131 --> 00:51:44.897
- Who are you?
- I'm Holly. Holly Golightly.

530
00:51:45.469 --> 00:51:47.630
That doesn't sound like a real name.

531
00:51:47.638 --> 00:51:51.335
It isn't. I borrowed it.
You can do that up here.

532
00:51:51.342 --> 00:51:54.004
Up here? You mean in heaven.

533
00:51:55.980 --> 00:51:58.346
- You're funny.
- What's funny about it?

534
00:51:58.449 --> 00:52:00.815
This isn't heaven. You're not there yet.

535
00:52:02.286 --> 00:52:06.347
- What is this place?
- This place is not really one place

536
00:52:06.357 --> 00:52:08.985
and also is not the other place.

537
00:52:10.794 --> 00:52:12.455
It's bits of both!

538
00:52:19.336 --> 00:52:22.100
- What is that?
- That's where we're going.

539
00:52:23.874 --> 00:52:26.866
<i>Holly said there was a wide.
wide heaven</i>

540
00:52:26.977 --> 00:52:29.002
<i>beyond everything we knew.</i>

541
00:52:32.182 --> 00:52:34.377
<i>where there was no cornfield.</i>

542
00:52:35.019 --> 00:52:36.350
<i>no memory.</i>

543
00:52:37.354 --> 00:52:38.651
<i>no grave.</i>

544
00:52:42.393 --> 00:52:44.725
<i>But I wasn't looking beyond yet.</i>

545
00:52:46.563 --> 00:52:48.554
<i>I was still looking back.</i>

546
00:52:57.841 --> 00:52:59.502
<i>You can't go back.</i>

547
00:53:02.846 --> 00:53:04.211
Who are you?

548
00:53:05.849 --> 00:53:08.374
It's over. Come with me.

549
00:53:08.919 --> 00:53:10.546
I don't know you.

550
00:53:11.722 --> 00:53:13.713
Why are you here?

551
00:53:13.724 --> 00:53:16.386
You need to let go of Earth.

552
00:53:16.393 --> 00:53:19.260
You're dead. Susie. You have to leave.

553
00:53:22.232 --> 00:53:23.859
I have to go home.

554
00:54:17.321 --> 00:54:18.413
Dad!

555
00:55:22.519 --> 00:55:25.352
<i>My murderer began to feel safe.</i>

556
00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:28.483
<i>He knew people wanted to move on.</i>

557
00:55:29.193 --> 00:55:31.058
<i>They needed to forget.</i>

558
00:55:31.995 --> 00:55:34.054
<i>He took comfort in the thought.</i>

559
00:55:34.665 --> 00:55:36.690
<i>No one was looking at him.</i>

560
00:55:46.543 --> 00:55:50.809
<i>But there was one thing
my murderer didn't understand.</i>

561
00:55:53.016 --> 00:55:58.010
<i>He didn't understand
how much a father could love his child.</i>

562
00:56:35.058 --> 00:56:36.286
Dad!

563
00:57:10.160 --> 00:57:11.491
It's okay.

564
00:57:12.930 --> 00:57:14.795
It's going to be okay.

565
00:57:15.632 --> 00:57:19.625
He knows I'm here.
My dad knows I'm here.

566
00:57:21.972 --> 00:57:23.803
<i>I was still with him.</i>

567
00:57:27.978 --> 00:57:31.846
<i>I wasn't lost. or frozen or gone.</i>

568
00:57:32.983 --> 00:57:34.416
<i>I was alive.</i>

569
00:57:35.419 --> 00:57:39.321
<i>I was alive in my own perfect world.</i>

570
00:58:54.197 --> 00:58:55.562
Dad?

571
00:58:56.733 --> 00:58:58.166
I saw Susie.

572
00:59:02.172 --> 00:59:04.037
She came into my room.

573
00:59:05.575 --> 00:59:08.009
She kissed me on the cheek.

574
00:59:08.078 --> 00:59:09.705
Come here. buddy.

575
00:59:13.917 --> 00:59:15.407
I saw her. too.

576
00:59:16.753 --> 00:59:18.584
- Dad?
- Yeah?

577
00:59:19.089 --> 00:59:20.886
I think she listens.

578
00:59:35.272 --> 00:59:37.968
<i>She's used up all the film
we gave her for her birthday.</i>

579
00:59:37.974 --> 00:59:39.271
<i>All of it?</i>

580
00:59:39.376 --> 00:59:42.539
<i>It's a crime
to be creative in this family.</i>

581
00:59:42.612 --> 00:59:45.137
<i>Say we pay for 1 roll a month?</i>

582
00:59:45.148 --> 00:59:46.308
<i>1 roll a month?</i>

583
00:59:51.621 --> 00:59:52.952
I got them.

584
00:59:53.790 --> 00:59:56.418
Look at these. Some of these are good.

585
00:59:59.129 --> 01:00:01.290
Honey. why don't you get them
all developed?

586
01:00:01.398 --> 01:00:04.492
- This 1 roll a month thing is...
- This must be one of her artistic shots.

587
01:00:04.501 --> 01:00:07.231
- really crazy. honey. It's crazy.
- Why?

588
01:00:07.304 --> 01:00:10.501
I mean. why do we wanna keep this thing
dragging out like this?

589
01:00:10.607 --> 01:00:13.804
We're not dragging it out.
We made a deal.

590
01:00:13.810 --> 01:00:15.744
There is no deal. Jack.

591
01:00:31.962 --> 01:00:33.827
- Fenerman...
- Len. I had to call you.

592
01:00:33.830 --> 01:00:36.856
<i>Look. Susie is a smart kid.
She would never go off with a stranger.</i>

593
01:00:36.867 --> 01:00:39.859
<i>It had to be someone she knew.
somebody local.</i>

594
01:00:39.870 --> 01:00:42.031
...I'd play with it all the time.

595
01:00:42.339 --> 01:00:45.103
<i>Look. I've got a name for you.
I've got several names. actually.</i>

596
01:00:45.120 --> 01:00:46.362
<i>Ronald Driver.</i>

597
01:00:46.363 --> 01:00:47.867
Do you have an address?

598
01:00:48.445 --> 01:00:52.506
<i>Len. I've got another name for you.
He's a janitor. Michael Gitchell.</i>

599
01:00:53.884 --> 01:00:57.342
<i>There's something wrong with
this one. I'm telling you. Gary Davis.</i>

600
01:00:57.354 --> 01:00:58.514
- Who's that?
- Davis.

601
01:00:58.522 --> 01:00:59.955
He works in the sanitation department.

602
01:01:00.023 --> 01:01:01.957
<i>Okay. I'll look into it. Jack.</i>

603
01:01:02.025 --> 01:01:03.049
But I have his address right here.

604
01:01:03.160 --> 01:01:05.355
Is it a bad thing if I just drop by there
and take a look myself?

605
01:01:07.831 --> 01:01:09.731
<i>- Fenerman.
- Have you checked on Frank Peretti yet?</i>

606
01:01:09.833 --> 01:01:12.700
<i>- Who?
- Peretti. P-E-R-E-T-T-I.</i>

607
01:01:12.802 --> 01:01:14.702
<i>I have his credit report. Len.
It does not look good.</i>

608
01:01:14.804 --> 01:01:16.362
<i>I'm on top of it.
You understand?</i>

609
01:01:16.473 --> 01:01:18.532
<i>- Len. I found another one.
- Jack. listen.</i>

610
01:01:18.542 --> 01:01:21.841
<i>you got to trust me. okay?
We're gonna get this guy.</i>

611
01:01:24.214 --> 01:01:26.705
Len! Glad you're here.
I was just going to call you.

612
01:01:26.716 --> 01:01:28.047
Yeah. I got your messages.

613
01:01:28.151 --> 01:01:29.641
I've been at the Public Records Office
all day.

614
01:01:29.719 --> 01:01:31.346
Got a lot of stuff to go over here.

615
01:01:31.655 --> 01:01:33.748
I know you're looking
at the obvious suspects.

616
01:01:33.857 --> 01:01:36.655
convicted felons. child molesters.
And I understand why.

617
01:01:36.726 --> 01:01:39.593
but. Len. I think you're coming at it
from the wrong angle.

618
01:01:39.696 --> 01:01:42.426
- Honey...
- Herman Stolfuz just across the street.

619
01:01:42.432 --> 01:01:44.900
Now. he appears to be perfectly normal.
but. Len.

620
01:01:45.869 --> 01:01:48.838
- the man wears adult diapers.
- Herman is 80 years old.

621
01:01:48.905 --> 01:01:52.397
I followed him in the supermarket.
His shopping cart was filled with them.

622
01:01:52.409 --> 01:01:54.400
- He has a prostate problem.
- My point is.

623
01:01:54.411 --> 01:01:56.242
we need to start working backwards.

624
01:01:56.346 --> 01:02:00.009
Start looking at family histories.
criminal records. mental health issues.

625
01:02:00.083 --> 01:02:01.243
I've been doing a lot of reading
on this subject.

626
01:02:01.351 --> 01:02:04.616
- Jack. this doesn't change anything.
- Did I mention taxes? Len.

627
01:02:04.621 --> 01:02:06.111
you can tell a lot about a person
from taxes.

628
01:02:06.223 --> 01:02:09.090
Please. will you just stop it now?
Will you just stop?

629
01:02:09.192 --> 01:02:11.422
Can't you just leave it alone?

630
01:02:14.531 --> 01:02:17.466
Jack. I know it's been 11 months.

631
01:02:17.467 --> 01:02:20.095
I know you've been trying
to deal with this in your own way.

632
01:02:21.638 --> 01:02:25.130
but she's not coping very well.
She needs help. Jack.

633
01:02:26.710 --> 01:02:29.770
She needs someone
to help her get through this.

634
01:02:35.585 --> 01:02:38.952
Grandma's here!
Grandma! Grandma's here!

635
01:02:40.457 --> 01:02:42.550
What's my mother doing here?

636
01:02:42.626 --> 01:02:44.218
Look. you're not coping. okay?

637
01:02:44.294 --> 01:02:46.990
Len's worried. I'm worried.
Your mother offered to help.

638
01:02:46.997 --> 01:02:48.555
You invited her here?

639
01:02:48.965 --> 01:02:51.559
- Darling!
- Hello. Mother.

640
01:02:51.635 --> 01:02:53.125
- Watch the hair. sweetheart.
- Sorry.

641
01:02:53.236 --> 01:02:56.330
- Look at you. Are you eating?
- Is this all of it?

642
01:02:56.339 --> 01:02:58.739
Don't be ridiculous.
That's just my makeup.

643
01:02:58.808 --> 01:03:01.299
You are still handsome as hell. Jack.

644
01:03:01.811 --> 01:03:03.904
Lindsey. honey.
aren't you going to say hello?

645
01:03:04.347 --> 01:03:06.975
- The child hates me.
- Come here. buddy.

646
01:03:07.083 --> 01:03:09.415
So. what'll it be. Jack?

647
01:03:10.086 --> 01:03:12.020
Actually. I'm not drinking these days.

648
01:03:12.122 --> 01:03:13.987
Well. that's your problem in a nutshell.

649
01:03:16.593 --> 01:03:17.992
Are we still a family?

650
01:03:17.994 --> 01:03:19.655
Of course we're a family.

651
01:03:19.663 --> 01:03:22.257
Your mother's in crisis.
your father's a wreck.

652
01:03:22.332 --> 01:03:24.300
What does that make you?

653
01:03:26.369 --> 01:03:28.132
I'm in charge.

654
01:04:46.583 --> 01:04:48.881
...through the woods.
looking for fuzzwalker.

655
01:04:49.853 --> 01:04:54.256
Then he sees three. And he takes
his gun and looks and aims.

656
01:04:54.257 --> 01:04:56.122
And then. a giant puff of smoke!

657
01:04:56.126 --> 01:04:59.459
He doesn't see them anymore.
Then he realizes that was his gun.

658
01:04:59.462 --> 01:05:04.126
It was out of bullets! Then he runs.
Runs. runs. runs. runs. runs!

659
01:05:04.134 --> 01:05:05.465
Till he runs in the forest.

660
01:05:05.468 --> 01:05:09.097
but then he realizes
he came without his fuzzwalker.

661
01:05:26.956 --> 01:05:28.218
Holiday!

662
01:05:39.769 --> 01:05:41.327
All right! Okay!

663
01:05:49.345 --> 01:05:51.472
You're a Salmon girl. right?

664
01:05:56.085 --> 01:05:57.143
Okay.

665
01:05:58.855 --> 01:05:59.981
Okay.

666
01:06:05.662 --> 01:06:06.924
Holiday.

667
01:06:16.272 --> 01:06:17.500
Grandma?

668
01:06:18.675 --> 01:06:20.540
I know where Susie is.

669
01:06:20.877 --> 01:06:24.176
Yeah. Susie's gone
to heaven. sweetheart.

670
01:06:24.180 --> 01:06:26.671
Lindsey said there is no heaven.

671
01:06:26.783 --> 01:06:28.842
All right. then. she's dead.

672
01:06:30.687 --> 01:06:32.712
You might be dead soon.

673
01:06:32.722 --> 01:06:35.520
- Why do you say that?
- Because you're old.

674
01:06:36.726 --> 01:06:38.193
Thirtyfive is not old.

675
01:06:38.194 --> 01:06:41.288
You've been sniffing
too much of that nail polish.

676
01:06:41.364 --> 01:06:43.628
And.. anyway.
nothing is going to happen to me.

677
01:06:43.700 --> 01:06:45.167
You know why?

678
01:06:46.836 --> 01:06:49.896
Because I take my medicine every day.

679
01:06:52.342 --> 01:06:53.673
Grandma.

680
01:06:55.378 --> 01:06:56.743
she's here.

681
01:06:57.247 --> 01:06:58.714
- What?
- Susie.

682
01:07:00.083 --> 01:07:02.074
Susie's in the in-between.

683
01:07:18.034 --> 01:07:21.834
<i>I was in the blue horizon.
between heaven and Earth.</i>

684
01:07:23.273 --> 01:07:25.264
<i>The days were unchanging.</i>

685
01:07:26.576 --> 01:07:30.410
<i>and every night.
I dreamed the same dream.</i>

686
01:07:32.916 --> 01:07:34.884
<i>The smell of damp earth.</i>

687
01:07:35.718 --> 01:07:37.913
<i>The scream that no one heard.</i>

688
01:07:39.722 --> 01:07:44.284
<i>The sound of my heart beating.
like a hammer against cloth.</i>

689
01:07:48.264 --> 01:07:50.459
<i>And I would hear them calling.</i>

690
01:07:51.434 --> 01:07:53.800
<i>the voices of the dead.</i>

691
01:07:56.773 --> 01:07:58.798
<i>I wanted to follow them.</i>

692
01:07:58.808 --> 01:08:00.469
<i>to find a way out.</i>

693
01:08:01.978 --> 01:08:05.311
<i>but I would always come back
to the same door.</i>

694
01:08:07.750 --> 01:08:09.377
<i>And I was afraid.</i>

695
01:08:13.056 --> 01:08:15.490
<i>I knew if I went in there.</i>

696
01:08:17.393 --> 01:08:19.293
<i>I would never come out.</i>

697
01:08:26.135 --> 01:08:29.627
<i>My murderer could live in one moment
for a long time.</i>
